If you want to stick to the promise/async/await recipe, then you can do it this way:
```
// service
getData() {
    return this.http.get(this.url).toPromise();
}

// component
async ngOnInit() {
    this.users = await this.dataservice.getData();
    console.log(this.users);
    next_function();
```

You don&#39;t need to use `async`/`await` here at all. You are already using `toPromise` in `getData` to convert the observable to a promise. You can simply return this promise and handle the rest in the component.
```js
getData() {
    return this.http.get(this.url).toPromise();
}
```
Now use `then` in `ngOnInit` to get the resolved/rejected data.
```js
ngOnInit() {
    this.dataservice.getData().then(users =&gt; {
        console.log(users);
        next_function();
    }, err =&gt; {
        console.log(err);
    });
}
```

This way if you call `getData` from different components, you can handle any API errors in that component. You may also want to check out [observables][1].


